          "body": "The chapter opens with Samuel reminding Saul of the source and the scope of his authority: 'The LORD sent me to anoint you as king over His people, over Israel' (15:1). The anointing is not merely a ceremony; it is a relationship of accountability. The greater the gift, the greater the demand. The commission that follows is total: 'utterly destroy all that he has... do not spare him' (15:3). The Hebrew *cherem* — devoted to destruction — was Israel's legal instrument of holy war, an act of worship in which the enemy and all his goods were surrendered entirely to God rather than appropriated by the victors. The command was not militarily pragmatic; it was theologically absolute. There was no category of 'the best animals' that could be exempted. The chapter's entire conflict is established in these three verses: God has spoken with total specificity, and Saul will obey with selective specificity."
