        "excerpt": "Now go and strike Amalek and utterly destroy all that he has, and do not spare him; but put to death both man and woman, child and infant, ox and sheep, camel and donkey.",
        "body": "The command to execute *cherem* against Amalek is among the most difficult passages in the Old Testament for modern readers, and it demands honest engagement rather than evasion. The *cherem* — the sacred ban — was not arbitrary genocidal policy; it was the theological enactment of God's covenantal judgment against a people whose sin had reached its full measure (cf. Genesis 15:16 on the Amorites). Deuteronomy 20:16-18 explains the rationale: total destruction was designed to prevent Israel from adopting the abominations of Canaan's religious culture. The Amalekites had struck Israel from behind during the Exodus, targeting the weak and the stragglers (Deuteronomy 25:17-18), a moral cowardice God declared He would repay. The command arrives in 1 Samuel 15 as the delayed execution of a sentence already pronounced in Exodus 17:14-16, where God declared perpetual war with Amalek.\n\nThe key to understanding the *cherem* command is that it is an act of worship before it is an act of war. By surrendering the enemy and all his goods entirely to God rather than keeping plunder, Israel acknowledged that victory belonged to God alone and that they had no claim on what He destroyed. The moment Saul treats the best animals as resources to be applied to his own purposes — even religious purposes like sacrifice — he has violated the logic of *cherem* entirely. He has substituted his own assessment of value for God's command. This is not a minor tactical deviation; it is a theological inversion of the entire act.\n\nThe inclusion of women, children, and livestock in the *cherem* command has generated substantial scholarly discussion. Orthodox evangelical scholars, including Douglas Stuart (*Hosea-Jonah*, WBC) and John Goldingay, locate this within the ancient Near Eastern understanding of corporate solidarity: the family and household of a guilty nation share in the consequence of that nation's corporate guilt. This does not imply that individual Amalekite women and infants were morally culpable in the same degree as the warriors; it implies that the *cherem* is a covenantal act of corporate judgment, not a verdict on individual moral desert. The permanent abrogation of this kind of command in the New Covenant (where no nation is now God's theocratic instrument of judgment) is what makes it inapplicable today — not the inadequacy of the Old Covenant theology, but its fulfillment in Christ who bears the full weight of divine judgment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Charam* (utterly destroy) derives from the noun *cherem* — that which is devoted, set apart, made sacred to God by destruction. *Chamal* (spare, v.3) — to have pity, to spare out of felt compassion. The two verbs are the chapter's axis: *charam* is what God commands; *chamal* is what Saul and the people do instead."
