        "excerpt": "But Saul and the people spared Agag and the best of the sheep, the oxen, the fatlings, the lambs, and all that was good, and were not willing to destroy them utterly; but everything despised and worthless, that they utterly destroyed.",
        "body": "Verse 9 is the chapter's narrative indictment, and its structure is precise. The subject is 'Saul and the people' — the king and his army are jointly responsible. The verb is *chamal* (spared) — the exact word God's command used in 15:3 ('do not spare him'). The object is 'Agag and the best of the sheep, the oxen, the fatlings, the lambs, and all that was good.' Then comes the editorial comment: 'they were not willing to destroy them.' This is not a language of inability or oversight; it is a language of volitional refusal. They could have obeyed. They chose not to. And then the grotesque inversion: 'everything despised and worthless, that they utterly destroyed.' They executed the *cherem* on what had no value and kept what did. They performed obedience precisely where it cost nothing.\n\nThis pattern — obey selectively, keep the best, destroy only what you did not want anyway — is what Howard Hendricks and Charles Swindoll both describe as the most common form of practical disobedience: not outright defiance, but a redefinition of the command to fit what the obedient person was already inclined to do. Saul did not dismiss God's command; he modified it. He applied it to the category of Amalekites who were worthless and exempted the category that was valuable. This is the architecture of rationalized disobedience, and it is entirely recognizable in the present reader's life.\n\nThe monument at Carmel (15:12) is the chapter's psychological portrait of Saul's interior state. He erects a *yad* — a hand-stele, a self-memorial — at the site of his victory before he encounters Samuel, before any prophetic or divine evaluation of his conduct. He is celebrating an obedience he has not actually rendered. The self-monument is not incidental detail; it is the narrator's window into Saul's conscience. A man who knows he has failed does not build himself a monument before the reckoning. A man who has redefined obedience to mean 'what I chose to do' genuinely believes he has succeeded.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yad* (monument, literally 'hand,' 15:12) — a commemorative stele. The same word is used in Isaiah 56:5 for the memorial God gives the eunuch who keeps His covenant — a poignant contrast. Saul erects his own *yad*; God gives a *yad* to the faithful."
